{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12408"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12408"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.12,0.13,0.05,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4916"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4916"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"9587"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive fatigue and lethargy. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has a five pack-year smoking history and drinks about four cans of beer weekly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. He has noticeable skin hyperpigmentation, particularly on his knuckles and dorsal surface of the hands. The remainder of his physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis laboratory tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ehaemoglobin 142 g/L (130-180)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ewhite cell count 6.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eplatelets 220 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Esodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Epotassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ecreatinine 85 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EALT 30 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAST 35 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EALP 100 U/L (30-120)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGGT 40 U/L (5-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ebilirubin 15 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eserum iron 60 \u03bcmol/L (10-30)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Etransferrin saturation 82% (20-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eserum ferritin 830 \u03bcg/L (30-620)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther testing confirms haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a possible complication of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetes mellitus","Restrictive lung disease","Valvular heart disease","Parkinsonism","Acute pancreatitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with haemochromatosis, a genetic disorder characterised by excessive iron absorption and accumulation in various organs. The elevated serum iron, transferrin saturation, and ferritin levels, combined with the characteristic skin hyperpigmentation, support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-recognised complication of haemochromatosis, occurring in approximately 50% of patients with advanced disease. Iron deposition in pancreatic beta cells leads to their dysfunction and destruction, resulting in insulin deficiency. This is sometimes referred to as \u0022bronze diabetes\u0022 due to the associated skin pigmentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestrictive lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with haemochromatosis. This pulmonary complication is more characteristic of alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, another genetic condition that can cause both lung and liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValvular heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not a characteristic complication of haemochromatosis. While cardiac involvement does occur, it typically manifests as dilated cardiomyopathy and conduction abnormalities rather than valvular dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParkinsonism\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical complication of haemochromatosis. Neurological manifestations including movement disorders are more characteristic of Wilson\u0027s disease, another genetic disorder of metal metabolism involving copper accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised complication of haemochromatosis. While the pancreas is affected by iron deposition, this typically results in chronic pancreatitis and exocrine pancreatic dysfunction rather than acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemochromatosis is characterised by excessive iron absorption from the diet, leading to iron accumulation in various organs including the liver, pancreas, and heart.","Diabetes mellitus is a major complication of haemochromatosis resulting from iron deposition in pancreatic beta cells.","Early diagnosis and treatment with phlebotomy can prevent or reverse many complications of haemochromatosis."],"references":["European Association for the Study of the Liver; European Association for the Study of the Liver. EASL Clinical Practice Guidelines on haemochromatosis. J Hepatol. 2022 Aug;77(2):479-502. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35662478/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12408"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91363"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T19:16:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T19:19:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4916"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108993"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"